lie","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1430–":"omkring 1430–Afdød","1415–1507":"1415–1507","1450–1494":"1450–1494","1430–Female":"1430–Afdød","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1494":"1494","1507":"1507","about 1430":"omkring 1430","1549":"1549","Hereford, Herefordshire Unitary Authority, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1430–":"circa 1430–Overleden","1415–1507":"1415–1507","1450–1494":"1450–1494","1430–Female":"1430–Overleden","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1494":"1494","1507":"1507","about 1430":"circa 1430","1549":"1549","Hereford, Herefordshire Unitary Authority, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1430–":"about 1430–Deceased","1415–1507":"1415–1507","1450–1494":"1450–1494","1430–Female":"1430–Deceased","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1494":"1494","1507":"1507","about 1430":"about 1430","1549":"1549","Hereford, Herefordshire Unitary Authority, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Apleby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, and Cumbria, named from Old English <i>æppel</i> or Old Norse <i>epli</i> ‘apple’ + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farm’."],"variants":[{"name":"Applebee","meanings":["English: variant of   Appleby  ."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705201,"age":119,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. James Apleby was born about 1430, in Herefordshire, England. She married James Appleby in 1451, in Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1430–":"umbes 1430–Surnud","1415–1507":"1415–1507","1450–1494":"1450–1494","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1494":"1494","1507":"1507","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1549":"1549","Hereford, Herefordshire Unitary Authority, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1430–":"noin 1430–Kuollut","1415–1507":"1415–1507","1450–1494":"1450–1494","1430–Female":"1430–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1494":"1494","1507":"1507","about 1430":"noin 1430","1549":"1549","Hereford, Herefordshire Unitary Authority, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1430–":"environ 1430–Décédée","1415–1507":"1415–1507","1450–1494":"1450–1494","1430–Female":"1430–Décédée","1415":"1415","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1494":"1494","1507":"1507","about 1430":"environ 1430","1549":"1549","Hereford, Herefordshire Unitary Authority, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Angleterre","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. James Apleby est née environ 1